1. Add a `realization` field to the leg table.
Use:
- `realized cash`
- `accrued claim`
- `unrealized mtm`
- `in-kind incentive`

`leg_type` alone is still a bit too coarse. This matters because many DeFi dashboards mix collectible fees, accrued but unpaid carry, and mark-to-market PnL.

2. Add `edge strength` or `confidence`.
Use a small ordinal scale such as:
- `hard`
- `strong`
- `soft`

Not every `funded-by-subsidy` or `shares-payer-base` link is equally binding. Morpho borrower demand that is clearly farm-driven is different from a looser macro correlation. If you do not encode confidence, the graph becomes too binary for real risk work.

So the clean final schema is:

`leg = leg_type | realization | direction | immediate payer -> ultimate source | mechanism_superclass | mechanism_subclass | primary short-risk | secondary risks | gross source | main drags | break condition`

`edge = from_leg -> to_leg | edge_type | edge_strength`

`wrapper = routing control | redemption priority | concentration | hidden correlation | governance control | opacity`

That resolves the last open questions well:

- Uniswap v3: fee leg and inventory leg are structurally distinct.
- MEV: validator access revenue and searcher extraction revenue cannot be merged.
- Morpho: productive mechanism can still sit on a `funded-by-subsidy` edge.
- Resolv-style wrappers: underlying economics and wrapper fragility stay separate.
- sUSDe: funding carry and incentive transfer become separate legs with separate break conditions.

The main tradeoff is usability. This is no longer a memetic “taxonomy”; it is a compact risk data model. That is a feature for PM work, but only if you enforce a very small controlled vocabulary and allow `unknown / mixed / low-confidence` values. Otherwise analysts will overfit the schema and fake precision.

So I would standardize exactly this, with one naming tweak:

- `Leg Ledger Graph` for the full framework
- `Risk-first view` as the default portfolio projection
- `Funding-source view` as the sustainability projection

That keeps the winner unchanged: `Framework E` only when implemented as a `Leg Ledger Graph`. The runner-up also stays unchanged: `D`, because it remains the best single stress view, just not the best full decomposition.
